    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay so thanks. its basically saying if i use a font or an image and someone says i stole it, i have to pay for the agency's lawyers and anything else? that feels like a huge amount of risk for just one project. how do people usually limit that kind of liability in these clauses?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, your interpretation is correct; it can mean you take on the legal risk for intellectual property claims stemming from your work. To limit this risk, freelancers often negotiate a \"cap\" on liability, meaning you only have to cover losses up to a certain dollar amount, or sometimes only your total project fee. They might also limit indemnification only to direct damages, excluding punitive or indirect losses. It's always best to negotiate these limits before signing.",
      "source": "target",
