    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. what about the part about \"third party claims\"? it's a bit vague. does that mean it could be anyone, even if i didn't do anything wrong on purpose? like if a huge company just decides to come after me for some reason? it feels like these clauses are designed to let people just attack you from out of nowhere and make you deal with the mess.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "\"Third-party claims\" means anyone outside of the contract—like a copyright holder or a client's competitor—could initiate a claim against the other party because of the work. It doesn't necessarily mean you did something intentionally wrong; sometimes, the mere existence of copyrighted material in the work is enough for them to claim infringement. These clauses are definitely broad, which is why you need to be extremely careful about the scope of what you are promising to defend.",
      "source": "target",
